README.md
     1→derive(Error)
     4→[<img alt="github" src="https://img.shields.io/badge/github-dtolnay/thiserror-8da0cb?style=for-the-badge&labelColor=555555&logo=github" height="20">](https://github.com/dtolnay/thiserror)
     5→[<img alt="crates.io" src="https://img.shields.io/crates/v/thiserror.svg?style=for-the-badge&color=fc8d62&logo=rust" height="20">](https://crates.io/crates/thiserror)
     6→[<img alt="docs.rs" src="https://img.shields.io/badge/docs.rs-thiserror-66c2a5?style=for-the-badge&labelColor=555555&logo=docs.rs" height="20">](https://docs.rs/thiserror)
     7→[<img alt="build status" src="https://img.shields.io/github/actions/workflow/status/dtolnay/thiserror/ci.yml?branch=master&style=for-the-badge" height="20">](https://github.com/dtolnay/thiserror/actions?query=branch%3Amaster)
     8→
     9→This library provides a convenient derive macro for the standard library's
    10→[`std::error::Error`] trait.
    11→
    12→[`std::error::Error`]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/error/trait.Error.html
    13→
    14→```toml
    15→[dependencies]
    16→thiserror = "2"
    17→```
    18→
    19→<br>
    20→
    21→## Example
    23→```rust
    24→use thiserror::Error;
    25→
    26→#[derive(Error, Debug)]
    27→pub enum DataStoreError {
    28→    #[error("data store disconnected")]
    29→    Disconnect(#[from] io::Error),
    30→    #[error("the data for key `{0}` is not available")]
    31→    Redaction(String),
    32→    #[error("invalid header (expected {expected:?}, found {found:?})")]
    33→    InvalidHeader {
    34→        expected: String,
    35→        found: String,
    36→    },
    37→    #[error("unknown data store error")]
    38→    Unknown,
    39→}
    40→```
    41→
    42→<br>
    43→
    44→## Details
    46→- Thiserror deliberately does not appear in your public API. You get the same
    47→  thing as if you had written an implementation of `std::error::Error` by hand,
    48→  and switching from handwritten impls to thiserror or vice versa is not a
    49→  breaking change.
    50→
    51→- Errors may be enums, structs with named fields, tuple structs, or unit
    52→  structs.
    53→
    54→- A `Display` impl is generated for your error if you provide `#[error("...")]`
    55→  messages on the struct or each variant of your enum, as shown above in the
    56→  example.
    57→
    58→  The messages support a shorthand for interpolating fields from the error.
    59→
    60→    - `#[error("{var}")]`&ensp;⟶&ensp;`write!("{}", self.var)`
    61→    - `#[error("{0}")]`&ensp;⟶&ensp;`write!("{}", self.0)`
    62→    - `#[error("{var:?}")]`&ensp;⟶&ensp;`write!("{:?}", self.var)`
    63→    - `#[error("{0:?}")]`&ensp;⟶&ensp;`write!("{:?}", self.0)`
    64→
    65→  These shorthands can be used together with any additional format args, which
    66→  may be arbitrary expressions. For example:
    67→
    68→  ```rust
    69→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
    70→  pub enum Error {
    71→      #[error("invalid rdo_lookahead_frames {0} (expected < {max})", max = i32::MAX)]
    72→      InvalidLookahead(u32),
    73→  }
    74→  ```
    75→
    76→  If one of the additional expression arguments needs to refer to a field of the
    77→  struct or enum, then refer to named fields as `.var` and tuple fields as `.0`.
    78→
    79→  ```rust
    80→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
    81→  pub enum Error {
    82→      #[error("first letter must be lowercase but was {:?}", first_char(.0))]
    83→      WrongCase(String),
    84→      #[error("invalid index {idx}, expected at least {} and at most {}", .limits.lo, .limits.hi)]
    85→      OutOfBounds { idx: usize, limits: Limits },
    86→  }
    87→  ```
    88→
    89→- A `From` impl is generated for each variant that contains a `#[from]`
    90→  attribute.
    91→
    92→  The variant using `#[from]` must not contain any other fields beyond the
    93→  source error (and possibly a backtrace &mdash; see below). Usually `#[from]`
    94→  fields are unnamed, but `#[from]` is allowed on a named field too.
    95→
    96→  ```rust
    97→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
    98→  pub enum MyError {
    99→      Io(#[from] io::Error),
   100→      Glob(#[from] globset::Error),
   101→  }
   102→  ```
   103→
      →…
   211→## Comparison to anyhow
   213→Use thiserror if you care about designing your own dedicated error type(s) so
   214→that the caller receives exactly the information that you choose in the event of
   215→failure. This most often applies to library-like code. Use [Anyhow] if you don't
   216→care what error type your functions return, you just want it to be easy. This is
   217→common in application-like code.
   218→
   219→[Anyhow]: https://github.com/dtolnay/anyhow
   220→
   221→<br>
   222→

